</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Gastrointestinal (GI) bleeding is a common clinical condition that is increasingly seen in an aging population and frequently requires hospitalization and intervention, with significant morbidity and mortality. Obscure GI bleeding (OGIB) is defined as loss of blood with no source identified after upper endoscopy and colonoscopy. Whether an obscure site of bleeding is clinically evident or silent, it constitutes a diagnostic and therapeutic challenge for the clinician. Gastroenterology and radiology provide the essential diagnostic tools used to evaluate suspected OGIB, each with its strengths and weaknesses. Small bowel series and conventional enteroclysis have a limited role in OGIB. Computed tomographic (CT) enterography and CT enteroclysis are noninvasive techniques with promising results in evaluation of small bowel disease and silent OGIB. CT angiography is a useful triaging tool for diagnosing or excluding active GI hemorrhage, localizing the site of bleeding, and guiding subsequent treatment. Tagged red blood cell scanning is the most sensitive technique for detection of active GI bleeding and allows imaging over a prolonged period, making it useful for detecting intermittent bleeding. Capsule endoscopy has emerged as an important tool for investigating OGIB, but it may soon have competition from double-balloon enteroscopy, a diagnostic technique that can also facilitate therapy.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.301095091">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.301095091">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c10a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1181" aria-labelledby="f10a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Intraluminal accumulation of radiotracer activity in a 75-year-old man who presented with intermittent bright rectal bleeding. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 30 minutes <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, and 4 hours <b>(d)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of intermittent bleeding (circle in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) in the left lower quadrant. The bleeding was from a distal small bowel source.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f10a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c10b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1113" aria-labelledby="f10b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Intraluminal accumulation of radiotracer activity in a 75-year-old man who presented with intermittent bright rectal bleeding. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 30 minutes <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, and 4 hours <b>(d)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of intermittent bleeding (circle in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) in the left lower quadrant. The bleeding was from a distal small bowel source.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f10b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10c-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c10c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1178" aria-labelledby="f10c-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Intraluminal accumulation of radiotracer activity in a 75-year-old man who presented with intermittent bright rectal bleeding. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 30 minutes <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, and 4 hours <b>(d)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of intermittent bleeding (circle in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) in the left lower quadrant. The bleeding was from a distal small bowel source.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f10c-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10d-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c10d.jpeg" height="1280" width="1120" aria-labelledby="f10d-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> Intraluminal accumulation of radiotracer activity in a 75-year-old man who presented with intermittent bright rectal bleeding. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 30 minutes <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, and 4 hours <b>(d)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of intermittent bleeding (circle in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) in the left lower quadrant. The bleeding was from a distal small bowel source.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f10d-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c11a.jpeg" height="1133" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Increasing intensity of intraluminal radiotracer activity over time in a 79-year-old woman who presented with melena. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 1 hour <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, 4 hours <b>(d)</b>, 5 hours <b>(e)</b>, 6 hours <b>(f)</b>, and 7 hours <b>(g)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of bleeding (arrow in <b>f</b> and <b>g</b>) in the ileum. The bleeding focus is apparent beginning at 5 hours.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f11a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c11b.jpeg" height="1146" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Increasing intensity of intraluminal radiotracer activity over time in a 79-year-old woman who presented with melena. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 1 hour <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, 4 hours <b>(d)</b>, 5 hours <b>(e)</b>, 6 hours <b>(f)</b>, and 7 hours <b>(g)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of bleeding (arrow in <b>f</b> and <b>g</b>) in the ileum. The bleeding focus is apparent beginning at 5 hours.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f11b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11c-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c11c.jpeg" height="1198" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11c-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Increasing intensity of intraluminal radiotracer activity over time in a 79-year-old woman who presented with melena. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 1 hour <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, 4 hours <b>(d)</b>, 5 hours <b>(e)</b>, 6 hours <b>(f)</b>, and 7 hours <b>(g)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of bleeding (arrow in <b>f</b> and <b>g</b>) in the ileum. The bleeding focus is apparent beginning at 5 hours.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f11c-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11d-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c11d.jpeg" height="1141" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11d-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span> Increasing intensity of intraluminal radiotracer activity over time in a 79-year-old woman who presented with melena. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 1 hour <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, 4 hours <b>(d)</b>, 5 hours <b>(e)</b>, 6 hours <b>(f)</b>, and 7 hours <b>(g)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of bleeding (arrow in <b>f</b> and <b>g</b>) in the ileum. The bleeding focus is apparent beginning at 5 hours.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f11d-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11e-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c11e.jpeg" height="1154" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11e-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11e</span> Increasing intensity of intraluminal radiotracer activity over time in a 79-year-old woman who presented with melena. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 1 hour <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, 4 hours <b>(d)</b>, 5 hours <b>(e)</b>, 6 hours <b>(f)</b>, and 7 hours <b>(g)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of bleeding (arrow in <b>f</b> and <b>g</b>) in the ileum. The bleeding focus is apparent beginning at 5 hours.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f11e-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11f-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c11f.jpeg" height="1207" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11f-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11f</span> Increasing intensity of intraluminal radiotracer activity over time in a 79-year-old woman who presented with melena. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 1 hour <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, 4 hours <b>(d)</b>, 5 hours <b>(e)</b>, 6 hours <b>(f)</b>, and 7 hours <b>(g)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of bleeding (arrow in <b>f</b> and <b>g</b>) in the ileum. The bleeding focus is apparent beginning at 5 hours.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f11f-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11g-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c11g.jpeg" height="1190" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11g-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11g</span> Increasing intensity of intraluminal radiotracer activity over time in a 79-year-old woman who presented with melena. Dynamic radionuclide images of the abdomen, obtained 1 hour <b>(a)</b>, 2 hours <b>(b)</b>, 3 hours <b>(c)</b>, 4 hours <b>(d)</b>, 5 hours <b>(e)</b>, 6 hours <b>(f)</b>, and 7 hours <b>(g)</b> after intravenous administration of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled RBCs, show a focus of bleeding (arrow in <b>f</b> and <b>g</b>) in the ileum. The bleeding focus is apparent beginning at 5 hours.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f11g-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g12a.jpeg" height="1088" width="1530" aria-labelledby="f12a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Active GI hemorrhage in a 67-year-old woman with melena and bleeding that obscured endoscopic findings. <b>(a)</b> Selective angiogram of the gastroduodenal artery shows contrast material extravasation into the duodenal lumen (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Gastroduodenal artery <b>(b)</b> and celiac trunk <b>(c)</b> angiograms, obtained after coil embolization (arrow), show stoppage of the GI bleeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f12a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g12b.jpeg" height="1126" width="1583" aria-labelledby="f12b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Active GI hemorrhage in a 67-year-old woman with melena and bleeding that obscured endoscopic findings. <b>(a)</b> Selective angiogram of the gastroduodenal artery shows contrast material extravasation into the duodenal lumen (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Gastroduodenal artery <b>(b)</b> and celiac trunk <b>(c)</b> angiograms, obtained after coil embolization (arrow), show stoppage of the GI bleeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f12b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12c-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g12c.jpeg" height="1128" width="1620" aria-labelledby="f12c-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Active GI hemorrhage in a 67-year-old woman with melena and bleeding that obscured endoscopic findings. <b>(a)</b> Selective angiogram of the gastroduodenal artery shows contrast material extravasation into the duodenal lumen (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Gastroduodenal artery <b>(b)</b> and celiac trunk <b>(c)</b> angiograms, obtained after coil embolization (arrow), show stoppage of the GI bleeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f12c-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c13a.jpeg" height="903" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f13a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Active GI hemorrhage in an 82-year-old man with hematochezia. <b>(a)</b> Colonoscopic image of the right colon shows a large quantity of blood, which obscures the colonoscopic findings. <b>(b)</b> Selective angiogram of the ileocolic artery shows contrast material extravasation into the colonic lumen (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Ileocolic artery angiogram obtained after coil embolization (arrow) shows stoppage of the GI bleeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f13a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g13b.jpeg" height="1270" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Active GI hemorrhage in an 82-year-old man with hematochezia. <b>(a)</b> Colonoscopic image of the right colon shows a large quantity of blood, which obscures the colonoscopic findings. <b>(b)</b> Selective angiogram of the ileocolic artery shows contrast material extravasation into the colonic lumen (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Ileocolic artery angiogram obtained after coil embolization (arrow) shows stoppage of the GI bleeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f13b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13c-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g13c.jpeg" height="1243" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13c-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> Active GI hemorrhage in an 82-year-old man with hematochezia. <b>(a)</b> Colonoscopic image of the right colon shows a large quantity of blood, which obscures the colonoscopic findings. <b>(b)</b> Selective angiogram of the ileocolic artery shows contrast material extravasation into the colonic lumen (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Ileocolic artery angiogram obtained after coil embolization (arrow) shows stoppage of the GI bleeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f13c-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g14a.jpeg" height="1225" width="1710" aria-labelledby="f14a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia (Osler-Weber-Rendu syndrome) in a 45-year-old man with anemia, epistaxis, and oral telangiectases. Images from catheter-directed angiography of the mesenteric vessels show small telangiectases in the dependence of the colon (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a larger vascular malformation in the wall of the left colon (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f14a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g14b.jpeg" height="1680" width="1728" aria-labelledby="f14b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia (Osler-Weber-Rendu syndrome) in a 45-year-old man with anemia, epistaxis, and oral telangiectases. Images from catheter-directed angiography of the mesenteric vessels show small telangiectases in the dependence of the colon (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a larger vascular malformation in the wall of the left colon (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f14b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c15a.jpeg" height="585" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f15a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Close-up <b>(a)</b> and panoramic <b>(b)</b> photographs of a wireless capsule endoscope (PillCam; Given Imaging, Yoqneam, Israel).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f15a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c15b.jpeg" height="1147" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f15b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Close-up <b>(a)</b> and panoramic <b>(b)</b> photographs of a wireless capsule endoscope (PillCam; Given Imaging, Yoqneam, Israel).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f15b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c16a.jpeg" height="1228" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f16a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Results of wireless capsule endoscopy in four patients with OGIB. Images from capsule endoscopy show small bowel lesions suspected of being responsible for bleeding: angiodysplasias (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), bleeding ileal ulceration (arrow in <b>c</b>), and a jejunal tumor (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f16a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c16b.jpeg" height="1209" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f16b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Results of wireless capsule endoscopy in four patients with OGIB. Images from capsule endoscopy show small bowel lesions suspected of being responsible for bleeding: angiodysplasias (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), bleeding ileal ulceration (arrow in <b>c</b>), and a jejunal tumor (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f16b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16c-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c16c.jpeg" height="1224" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f16c-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Results of wireless capsule endoscopy in four patients with OGIB. Images from capsule endoscopy show small bowel lesions suspected of being responsible for bleeding: angiodysplasias (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), bleeding ileal ulceration (arrow in <b>c</b>), and a jejunal tumor (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f16c-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16d-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c16d.jpeg" height="1206" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f16d-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span> Results of wireless capsule endoscopy in four patients with OGIB. Images from capsule endoscopy show small bowel lesions suspected of being responsible for bleeding: angiodysplasias (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), bleeding ileal ulceration (arrow in <b>c</b>), and a jejunal tumor (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f16d-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c17a.jpeg" height="1238" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f17a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Double-balloon enteroscope. <b>(a)</b> Close-up photograph shows the insufflated latex balloons at the distal end of the enteroscope. <b>(b, c)</b> Photographs show an overall view <b>(b)</b> and the controller mechanisms <b>(c)</b> of the enteroscope.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f17a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c17b.jpeg" height="1067" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f17b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><fi