height="1134" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f18d-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18d</span> Results of double-balloon enteroscopy in four patients with OGIB. Images from double-balloon enteroscopy show small bowel lesions suspected of being responsible for bleeding: angiodysplasias (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), ileal ulceration (arrow in <b>c</b>), and jejunal adenocarcinoma (arrow in <b>d</b>). Arrow in <b>b</b> = angiodysplasia treated with argon plasma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f18d-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091c19x.jpeg" height="955" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f19-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span> Algorithm for the imaging work-up of patients with OGIB. <i>DB</i> = double-balloon, <i>Mes</i> = mesenteric.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f19-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g01a.jpeg" height="1098" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Small bowel involvement in a 34-year-old woman with systemic lupus erythematosus who presented with lower abdominal pain, diarrhea, weight loss, anemia, and positive results from a fecal occult blood test. Axial enteric phase <b>(a)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(b)</b> CT images show ascites and marked mural thickening and target appearance of a small bowel loop (arrow), findings consistent with small bowel involvement by systemic lupus erythematosus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f1a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g01b.jpeg" height="1088" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Small bowel involvement in a 34-year-old woman with systemic lupus erythematosus who presented with lower abdominal pain, diarrhea, weight loss, anemia, and positive results from a fecal occult blood test. Axial enteric phase <b>(a)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(b)</b> CT images show ascites and marked mural thickening and target appearance of a small bowel loop (arrow), findings consistent with small bowel involvement by systemic lupus erythematosus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f1b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g02a.jpeg" height="1335" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Radiation enteritis in a 72-year-old woman with colicky abdominal pain and unexplained anemia. She had undergone external-beam radiation therapy to the pelvis for cervical carcinoma. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> maximum intensity projection (MIP) enteric phase images from CT enterography show ileal luminal narrowing and a thickened enhanced bowel wall (arrow), findings consistent with radiation enteritis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f2a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g02b.jpeg" height="1377" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Radiation enteritis in a 72-year-old woman with colicky abdominal pain and unexplained anemia. She had undergone external-beam radiation therapy to the pelvis for cervical carcinoma. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> maximum intensity projection (MIP) enteric phase images from CT enterography show ileal luminal narrowing and a thickened enhanced bowel wall (arrow), findings consistent with radiation enteritis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f2b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g03a.jpeg" height="1357" width="1727" aria-labelledby="f3a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Polypoid jejunal lesion in a 53-year-old man with positive results from a fecal occult blood test. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> MIP enteric phase images from CT enterography show a hyperattenuating polypoid lesion (arrow) in the jejunum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f3a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g03b.jpeg" height="1428" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Polypoid jejunal lesion in a 53-year-old man with positive results from a fecal occult blood test. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> MIP enteric phase images from CT enterography show a hyperattenuating polypoid lesion (arrow) in the jejunum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f3b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g04a.jpeg" height="1440" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f4a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Gastrointestinal stromal tumor in a 92-year-old man with anemia and positive results from a fecal occult blood test. <b>(a)</b> Axial enteric phase CT image shows aneurysmal dilatation of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal MIP enteric phase image from CT enteroclysis shows aneurysmal dilatation of the terminal ileum by an exophytic mass (bottom arrow). There is one hepatic metastasis (top arrow). The surgical specimen revealed a gastrointestinal stromal tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f4a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g04b.jpeg" height="1418" width="1458" aria-labelledby="f4b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Gastrointestinal stromal tumor in a 92-year-old man with anemia and positive results from a fecal occult blood test. <b>(a)</b> Axial enteric phase CT image shows aneurysmal dilatation of the terminal ileum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal MIP enteric phase image from CT enteroclysis shows aneurysmal dilatation of the terminal ileum by an exophytic mass (bottom arrow). There is one hepatic metastasis (top arrow). The surgical specimen revealed a gastrointestinal stromal tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f4b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g05a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Adenocarcinoma in a 60-year-old man with anemia and subacute bowel obstruction. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> MIP portal venous phase images from CT enteroclysis show parietal thickening and enhancement of the proximal jejunum (arrow in <b>a</b>, circle in <b>b</b>), resultant marked stenosis, and dilatation of the proximal small bowel. The surgical specimen revealed adenocarcinoma<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f5a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g05b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1407" aria-labelledby="f5b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Adenocarcinoma in a 60-year-old man with anemia and subacute bowel obstruction. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> MIP portal venous phase images from CT enteroclysis show parietal thickening and enhancement of the proximal jejunum (arrow in <b>a</b>, circle in <b>b</b>), resultant marked stenosis, and dilatation of the proximal small bowel. The surgical specimen revealed adenocarcinoma<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f5b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g06a.jpeg" height="1338" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Active colonic bleeding in a 69-year-old man with massive hematochezia from an ileotransversostomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a fluid-filled transverse colonic loop (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and portal phase <b>(c)</b> CT images, obtained at the same level, show highly attenuating extravasated contrast material (arrow) in the lumen of the transverse colon. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> MIP CT images show active bleeding into the transverse colon (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f6a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g06b.jpeg" height="1362" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Active colonic bleeding in a 69-year-old man with massive hematochezia from an ileotransversostomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a fluid-filled transverse colonic loop (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and portal phase <b>(c)</b> CT images, obtained at the same level, show highly attenuating extravasated contrast material (arrow) in the lumen of the transverse colon. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> MIP CT images show active bleeding into the transverse colon (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f6b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6c-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g06c.jpeg" height="1355" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6c-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Active colonic bleeding in a 69-year-old man with massive hematochezia from an ileotransversostomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a fluid-filled transverse colonic loop (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and portal phase <b>(c)</b> CT images, obtained at the same level, show highly attenuating extravasated contrast material (arrow) in the lumen of the transverse colon. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> MIP CT images show active bleeding into the transverse colon (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f6c-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6d-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g06d.jpeg" height="1380" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6d-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span> Active colonic bleeding in a 69-year-old man with massive hematochezia from an ileotransversostomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a fluid-filled transverse colonic loop (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and portal phase <b>(c)</b> CT images, obtained at the same level, show highly attenuating extravasated contrast material (arrow) in the lumen of the transverse colon. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> MIP CT images show active bleeding into the transverse colon (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f6d-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6e-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g06e.jpeg" height="1590" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6e-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6e</span> Active colonic bleeding in a 69-year-old man with massive hematochezia from an ileotransversostomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image shows a fluid-filled transverse colonic loop (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and portal phase <b>(c)</b> CT images, obtained at the same level, show highly attenuating extravasated contrast material (arrow) in the lumen of the transverse colon. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> MIP CT images show active bleeding into the transverse colon (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f6e-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g07a.jpeg" height="1343" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Large vascular lesion in a 71-year-old man with massive hematochezia. (Results of colonoscopy were inconclusive owing to excess fluid and massive hemorrhage.) <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced conventional CT image shows fluid-filled colonic loops. <b>(b)</b> Axial enteric phase conventional CT image, obtained at the same level, shows highly attenuating extravasated contrast material (arrow) in the lumen of the descending colon. The patient underwent surgical treatment, which confirmed the presence of a large vascular lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f7a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g07b.jpeg" height="1356" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Large vascular lesion in a 71-year-old man with massive hematochezia. (Results of colonoscopy were inconclusive owing to excess fluid and massive hemorrhage.) <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced conventional CT image shows fluid-filled colonic loops. <b>(b)</b> Axial enteric phase conventional CT image, obtained at the same level, shows highly attenuating extravasated contrast material (arrow) in the lumen of the descending colon. The patient underwent surgical treatment, which confirmed the presence of a large vascular lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f7b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g08a.jpeg" height="1226" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Jejunal varices in a 59-year-old man with melena and anemia. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase conventional CT image shows thrombosis of the superior mesenteric vein (circle) and high-attenuation dilated and tortuous variceal structures along the jejunal wall (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal MIP portal venous phase CT image shows high-attenuation dilated and tortuous variceal structures along the jejunal wall (arrows), findings indicative of jejunal varices.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f8a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g08b.jpeg" height="1171" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Jejunal varices in a 59-year-old man with melena and anemia. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase conventional CT image shows thrombosis of the superior mesenteric vein (circle) and high-attenuation dilated and tortuous variceal structures along the jejunal wall (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal MIP portal venous phase CT image shows high-attenuation dilated and tortuous variceal structures along the jejunal wall (arrows), findings indicative of jejunal varices.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f8b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9a-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g09a.jpeg" height="1292" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9a-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Aortoenteric fistula in a 73-year-old man with a history of aortic repair who presented with acute anemia and melena. Axial arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(b)</b> conventional CT images show inflammatory alterations and gas surrounding the aortic graft. The fourth portion of the duodenum is closely adjacent to the aorta, with a fistulous tract (arrow) between the two structures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f9a-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9b-0300235" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095091/asset/images/g095091g09b.jpeg" height="1288" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9b-0300235" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Aortoenteric fistula in a 73-year-old man with a history of aortic repair who presented with acute anemia and melena. Axial arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(b)</b> conventional CT images show inflammatory alterations and gas surrounding the aortic graft. The fourth portion of the duodenum is closely adjacent to the aorta, with a fistulous tract (arrow) between the two structures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095091&amp;id=f9b-0300235">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0300235" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">American Gastroenterological Association medical position statement: evaluation and management of occult and obscure gastrointestinal bleeding. <em>Gastroenterology</em> 2000;118(1):197–201.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0016-5085(00)70429-X">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10611169/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=American+Gastroenterological+Association+medical+position+statement%3A+evaluation+and+management+of+occult+and+obscure+gastrointestinal+bleeding&amp;publication_year=2000&amp;journal=Gastroenterology&amp;pages=197-201&amp;doi=10.1016%2FS0016-5085%2800%2970429-X&amp;pmid=10611169">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="b2-0300235" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Gralnek IMObscure-overt gastrointestinal bleeding. <em>Gastroenterology</em> 2005;128(5):1424–1430.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2005.03.067">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15887123/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Obscure-overt+gastrointestinal+bleeding&amp;author=IM+Gralnek&amp;publication_year=2005&amp;journal=Gastroenterology&amp;pages=1424-1430&amp;doi=10.1053%2Fj.gastro.2005.03.067&amp;pmid=15887123">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="b3-0300235" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Thompson JN, Salem RR, Hemingway AP, et al.Specialist investigation of obscure gastrointestinal bleeding. <em>Gut</em> 1987;28(1):47–51.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1136/gut.28.1.47">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3493190/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Specialist+investigation+of+obscure+gastrointestinal+bleeding&amp;author=JN+Thompson&amp;author=RR+Salem&amp;author=AP+Hemingway&amp;publication_year=1987&amp;journal=Gut&amp;pages=47-51&amp;doi=10.1136%2Fgut.28.1.47&amp;pmid=3493190">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="b4-0300235" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Raju GS, Gerson L, Das A, Lewis B